TLSv1-scan(8) -- scan local system for services using deprecated TLSv1.0 or TLSv1.1
=====================================================================================

## SYNOPSIS

`TLSv1-scan` [--host <hostname|IP>]

## DESCRIPTION

**TLSv1-scan** scans TCP listening ports and checks each one for TLSv1.0 or
TLSv1.1 support using `sslscan(1)`. By default it scans the local system; when
a remote host is given via `--host`, it discovers open ports with `nmap(1)` and
then probes each one with `sslscan(1)`.

For local scans, any service where those deprecated protocol versions are
enabled is reported with its owning process by querying `ss(8)` and `lsof(8)`.

When scanning localhost the program must be run as root.

## OPTIONS

  * `--host` <hostname|IP>:
    Hostname or IP address of the target to scan. Accepts hostnames, IPv4
    addresses, and IPv6 addresses. Defaults to `localhost` when omitted.

  * `--help`, `-h`:
    Print a usage message and exit.

## DEPENDENCIES

The following tools must be installed and available in `PATH`:

  * `sslscan`:
    Part of EPEL on RHEL-based systems.

  * `ss`:
    Part of the `iproute` package.

  * `lsof`:
    Part of the `lsof` package.

  * `netstat`:
    Part of the `net-tools` package.

  * `nmap`:
    Required only for remote host scanning (`--host` with a non-localhost
    target). Part of the `nmap` package.

## EXIT STATUS

  * `0`:
    Success.

  * `1`:
    The program was not run as root while scanning localhost, a required
    dependency was not found, or an invalid host name was supplied.

## AUTHOR

Written by Gratien D'haese.

## SEE ALSO

sslscan(1), nmap(1), ss(8), lsof(8), netstat(8)
